9. The satires as a biographical source. When we look into the satires for information with regard to the life of their author, we should use discretion ; for a poet is not necessarily his own biographer. Many a picture which he presents may be purely literary, due to the influence of department or of other writers, and may have no existence in fact. Even what seems to have a direct persona] reference should not in all cases be regarded as authoritative. We may¹ reasonably expect, however, to draw from the satires some inferences with regard to the poet's education and char- acter' and to fix approximately the period of his literary activity.

10. Dates of publication. Juvenal, like many other an- cient writers, published his satires in books at different timeS, and apparently in the order in which they now stand in the Mss.
